  "Idea": "This paper introduces a novel framework titled \u003cb\u003eInvariant Instrumental Variable Synthesis via Inverse Contrastive Moment Optimization (IIVS-ICMO)\u003c/b\u003e, which redefines the generation of instrumental variables in graph representation learning by integrating geometric invariance into the enforcement of unconditional moment restrictions. The core innovation lies in replacing traditional adversarial orthogonality and mutual information maximization with an \u003ci\u003einverse contrastive loss\u003c/i\u003e that explicitly separates the instrument's representational trajectory from confounder-sensitive subspaces while maintaining strong association with the treatment. We model the instrument generator as a differentiable function over graph diffusion operators (e.g., personalized PageRank or heat kernel embeddings), allowing the synthetic instrument Z to emerge as a nonlinear transformation of ego-network features that is invariant to latent confounding variations. The exogeneity condition E[Z | U] = 0 is reformulated as a contrastive divergence: we construct negative samples by perturbing node representations along high-gradient directions of a confounder predictor, and train the instrument generator to produce Z such that ||Z - Z_neg|| is maximized—thereby ensuring insensitivity to confounding shifts. Simultaneously, the relevance condition Cov(Z, T) ≠ 0 is enforced via a dual positive-pair construction where Z is aligned with counterfactual treatment variants under small interventions. The unconditional moment restriction E[Z(Y − g(T,X))] = 0 is embedded within a variational contrastive bound, enabling end-to-end optimization using a hybrid objective combining inverse contrastive loss, moment error minimization, and task-specific reconstruction. Crucially, we derive a theoretical connection between minimizing ICL and satisfying the rank condition for IV identification, providing justification for its use in causal estimation. The resulting representations are provably less sensitive to unobserved confounders and generalize better across domains. This work advances the state-of-the-art by transforming IV synthesis from a statistical constraint satisfaction problem into a geometric invariance learning task, making it particularly effective in dynamic, heterogeneous, or partially observed graphs. Applications span recommendation systems with selection bias, biological networks with genetic confounding, and social influence modeling where homophily induces spurious correlations.",
  "Title": "IIVS-ICMO: Invariant Instrumental Variable Synthesis via Inverse Contrastive Moment Optimization in Graph Representation Learning",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design comprises four rigorous phases. (1) \u003cb\u003eDynamic Synthetic Graph Generation\u003c/b\u003e: Construct time-evolving graphs using a latent-space SCM with drifting confounders and treatment mechanisms. Introduce distributional shifts across training and test sets to evaluate out-of-distribution generalization. Instruments are considered invalid if they correlate with future confounder states. (2) \u003cb\u003eModel Architecture Implementation\u003c/b\u003e: Design the instrument generator using a GNN-based diffusion encoder that computes neighborhood-aggregated features over multiple hops. Implement the inverse contrastive loss by training a confounder surrogate network on auxiliary tasks (e.g., predicting node clustering coefficient as a proxy), then generating negative samples via gradient ascent on this surrogate. Optimize L = λ₁·ICL(Z, Z_neg) + λ₂·||E[Z(Y − Ŷ)]||² + λ₃·−MI(Z, T_intervened), where T_intervened is a GNN-perturbed treatment. Use moving average updates for stability. (3) \u003cb\u003eBaseline Comparison\u003c/b\u003e: Benchmark against AIVS-DUMO, RCGRL, standard GNNs, and GAN-based IV methods. Metrics include causal risk (interventional MSE), F-statistic, Wasserstein distance between treatment effect estimates across domains, and fairness scores in biased recommendation tasks. (4) \u003cb\u003eReal-world Evaluation\u003c/b\u003e: Apply to (a) DBLP co-authorship graphs with career-stage confounding, (b) Pinterest-like user-item interaction graphs with popularity bias, and (c) Tox21 molecular graphs with scaffold-induced confounding. Ideal outcomes include: (i) lower interventional MSE than AIVS-DUMO under distribution shift, (ii) higher F-statistics (>15) indicating stronger instruments, (iii) improved cross-domain consistency in effect estimates, and (iv) ablation confirming that removing ICL degrades performance more than removing MI terms.",
